<paragraph id="8B806D06BF2BC227CC37B5DFE56A1853" blockId="36.[367,530,1002,1026]" box="[367,530,1002,1026]" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">
<figureCitation id="13047183BF2BC227CC37B5DFE56A1853" box="[367,530,1002,1026]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="37.[125,206,1049,1070]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1025]" captionTargetId="figure-470@37.[613,947,149,625]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Text-fig. 22. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of fragmentary stamens (a, b) with in situ pollen of Clavatipollenites sp. 1 (c–g); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Fragmentary tetrasporangiate stamens; c–e) Distal view of pollen grains showing large, rounded aperture and the irregular verrucate aperture membrane; f) Proximal view of pollen grains showing dense reticulum; g) Section through the fractured pollen wall showing foot layer, columellae and muri with faint supratectal ornamentation. Specimens, TV44-S105013 (a, c, d), TV44-S105019 (b, e–g). Scale bars 300 Μm (a, b), 6 Μm (c–f), 3 Μm (g)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386279/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Text-fig. 22a–g</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3253E8DBF2BC227CDFEB22FE6CF1B72" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B806D06BF2BC227CDFEB22FE5CA1982" blockId="36.[129,768,1049,1491]" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">
<materialsCitation id="3B57675BBF2BC227CDFEB22FE5D61982" collectionCode="J" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" specimenCount="1">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d r e m a r k s. The material comprises several fragments of small tetrasporangiate stamens with pollen in situ (
<figureCitation id="13047183BF2BC227CCE4B26FE5111823" box="[444,617,1114,1138]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="37.[125,206,1049,1070]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1025]" captionTargetId="figure-470@37.[613,947,149,625]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Text-fig. 22. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of fragmentary stamens (a, b) with in situ pollen of Clavatipollenites sp. 1 (c–g); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Fragmentary tetrasporangiate stamens; c–e) Distal view of pollen grains showing large, rounded aperture and the irregular verrucate aperture membrane; f) Proximal view of pollen grains showing dense reticulum; g) Section through the fractured pollen wall showing foot layer, columellae and muri with faint supratectal ornamentation. Specimens, TV44-S105013 (a, c, d), TV44-S105019 (b, e–g). Scale bars 300 Μm (a, b), 6 Μm (c–f), 3 Μm (g)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386279/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Text-fig. 22a, b</figureCitation>
). The anthers are up to about 
<quantity id="4CC7C0E3BF2BC227CC77B24FE6F718C0" box="[303,399,1146,1170]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" unit="mm" value="0.52">0.52 mm</quantity>
long. Pollen grains in situ within the stamens were described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAE10F7BF2BC227CCB9B2AFE5DE18E3" author="Friis, E. M. &amp; Pedersen, K. R. &amp; Crane, P. R." box="[481,678,1178,1202]" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" pagination="259 - 296" refId="ref76722" refString="Friis, E. M., Pedersen, K. R., Crane, P. R. (1999): Early angiosperm diversification: the diversity of pollen associated with angiosperm reproductive structures in Early Cre- taceous floras from Portugal. - Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden, 86: 259 - 296. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 2666179" type="journal article" year="1999">Friis et al. (1999)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<typeStatus id="5484D3A4BF2BC227CF89B2AFE58718E3" box="[721,767,1178,1202]" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">type</typeStatus>
<collectionCode id="ED2EF5C3BF2BC227CDD9B28FE7E81883" box="[129,144,1210,1234]" country="South Africa" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:14647" name="University of the Witwatersrand" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" type="Herbarium">J</collectionCode>
.1. The grains are monoaperturate and almost circular in equatorial outline, about 14–16 µm in diameter, semitectatereticulate with a homobrochate reticulum (
<figureCitation id="13047183BF2BC227CF16B2CFE58D1943" box="[590,757,1274,1298]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="37.[125,206,1049,1070]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1025]" captionTargetId="figure-470@37.[613,947,149,625]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Text-fig. 22. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of fragmentary stamens (a, b) with in situ pollen of Clavatipollenites sp. 1 (c–g); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Fragmentary tetrasporangiate stamens; c–e) Distal view of pollen grains showing large, rounded aperture and the irregular verrucate aperture membrane; f) Proximal view of pollen grains showing dense reticulum; g) Section through the fractured pollen wall showing foot layer, columellae and muri with faint supratectal ornamentation. Specimens, TV44-S105013 (a, c, d), TV44-S105019 (b, e–g). Scale bars 300 Μm (a, b), 6 Μm (c–f), 3 Μm (g)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386279/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Text-fig. 22c–f</figureCitation>
). Lumina are irregular and up to about 1.2 µm in diameter. Muri are ornamented with tiny verrucae arranged in two rows. Columellae are of medium size and widely spaced (
<figureCitation id="13047183BF2BC227CDD0B34EE66019C2" box="[136,280,1403,1427]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="37.[125,206,1049,1070]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1025]" captionTargetId="figure-470@37.[613,947,149,625]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Text-fig. 22. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of fragmentary stamens (a, b) with in situ pollen of Clavatipollenites sp. 1 (c–g); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Fragmentary tetrasporangiate stamens; c–e) Distal view of pollen grains showing large, rounded aperture and the irregular verrucate aperture membrane; f) Proximal view of pollen grains showing dense reticulum; g) Section through the fractured pollen wall showing foot layer, columellae and muri with faint supratectal ornamentation. Specimens, TV44-S105013 (a, c, d), TV44-S105019 (b, e–g). Scale bars 300 Μm (a, b), 6 Μm (c–f), 3 Μm (g)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386279/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">
Text-fig. 
<quantity id="4CC7C0E3BF2BC227CDB4B34EE66019C2" box="[236,280,1403,1427]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.2" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" unit="g" value="22.0">22g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). The aperture is broad, rounded and covered by irregular verrucae that grade into the reticulum in the non-apertural regions of the grains (
<figureCitation id="13047183BF2BC227CCA7B38EE5DE1982" box="[511,678,1467,1491]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="37.[125,206,1049,1070]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1025]" captionTargetId="figure-470@37.[613,947,149,625]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Text-fig. 22. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of fragmentary stamens (a, b) with in situ pollen of Clavatipollenites sp. 1 (c–g); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a, b) Fragmentary tetrasporangiate stamens; c–e) Distal view of pollen grains showing large, rounded aperture and the irregular verrucate aperture membrane; f) Proximal view of pollen grains showing dense reticulum; g) Section through the fractured pollen wall showing foot layer, columellae and muri with faint supratectal ornamentation. Specimens, TV44-S105013 (a, c, d), TV44-S105019 (b, e–g). Scale bars 300 Μm (a, b), 6 Μm (c–f), 3 Μm (g)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386279/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Text-fig. 22c–e</figureCitation>
)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B806D06BF2BC227CDFEB3DEE6CF1B72" blockId="36.[129,768,1514,1827]" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">
A f f i n i t y a n d o t h e r o c c u r r e n c e s. In their general shape, form of the pollen wall, and the indistinctly delimitated aperture, these pollen grains are similar to various dispersed pollen assigned to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF2BC227CF1AB07EE5801A32" authorityName="COUPER" authorityYear="1958" box="[578,760,1611,1635]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Clavatipollenites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF2BC227CF1AB07EE5801A32" box="[578,760,1611,1635]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Clavatipollenites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Pollen grains of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF2BC227CC60B05EE6961AD2" authorityName="COUPER" authorityYear="1958" box="[312,494,1643,1667]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Clavatipollenites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF2BC227CC60B05EE6961AD2" box="[312,494,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Clavatipollenites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually compared to pollen of extant 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF2BC227CC64B0BEE6E41AF3" box="[316,412,1675,1698]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Ascarina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF2BC227CC64B0BEE6E41AF3" box="[316,412,1675,1698]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Ascarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the pollen described here differs from that of extant 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF2BC227CCB8B09EE5381A93" box="[480,576,1707,1730]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Ascarina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="36" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF2BC227CCB8B09EE5381A93" box="[480,576,1707,1730]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="189">Ascarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a very broad and rounded colpus. Similar pollen to the fossil grains described here also occur in several stamens recovered from the Catefica mesofossil flora.
</paragraph>
